%text
\[ \qquad \dydx = \yx - \cos^2\yx = F \left(\yx \right)\] Hence, this is obviously a \underline\text{homogenous} differential equation And to solve such a differential equation, we let $y = vx$. Hence, % \begin{align}
y = vx &\implies \underbrace{\dydx = v + x\dvdx}_{\text{Product Rule}} \\ \therefore v + x\dvdx &= \yx - \cos^2\yx = v - \cos^2 v \\ \frac{dv}{\cos^2 v} &= -\frac{dx}{x} \text{ or } \sec^2 v\cdot dv = -\frac{dx}{x} \end{align} %text %

%text
% \begin{align}
\sec^2 v\cdot dv &= -\frac{dx}{x} \\ \implies \int \sec^2v\cdot dv &= -\int \frac{dx}{x}\\ \text{or } \tan v &= -\log x + C \\ \text{or }\tan\yx + \log x &= C \quad \left(\because v = \yx \right) \\ \end{align}\\ %text But as the curve passes through $\pt$, therefore % \begin{align}
\tan \left(\dfrac{\frac\pi{4}}{1} \right) + \log 1 &= C \\ \implies C &= \tan\frac\pi{4} = 1 \end{align} %text And hence, the required curve is \[ \qquad \tan\yx + \log x = 1 \] %
